---

<Infographic
  title="Quantum teleportation"
  description="Quantum teleportation moves an unknown qubit's state from one location to another by consuming a shared Bell pair and sending two classical bits. No copy of the original state remains at the sender, consistent with no-cloning. This page covers the protocol, the resources it consumes, why it isn't faster than light, and its role as the link-layer 'send a qubit' primitive."
  references={[
    "bennett-prl-1993",
    "cacciapuoti-ieeetc-2020",
    "kozlowski-rfc9340",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "wootters-nature-1982",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="teleportation" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Quantum teleportation</h1>
        <p>
          A qubit cannot be copied — the no-cloning theorem forbids any unitary that
          duplicates an unknown <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. But a qubit's <em>state</em>
          can be moved from one place to another, by consuming a shared Bell pair and
          sending two classical bits over a classical channel. The state leaves the sender's
          qubit in the process — no copy of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> remains at the
          sender afterwards — and the destination ends up holding a different physical
          qubit in that same quantum state. This is <strong>quantum
          teleportation</strong> <SourceNote id="bennett-prl-1993" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          The network's job is to deliver Bell pairs; teleportation is what users do
          with them. Each qubit teleported consumes one Bell pair and two classical
          bits. In the entanglement-mediated architecture covered by 1G and 2G
          repeaters, this is the only way to move an unknown qubit between nodes —
          no-cloning forbids copying it, and any single photon carrying the state
          would be lost to channel attenuation long before reaching the far end. 3G
          repeaters take a different route: they send QEC-encoded photonic qubits
          directly down the channel and correct loss/operation errors at each hop,
          with no Bell pair or classical sideband involved. The repeaters page
          covers that contrast in detail.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="what" data-nav-section>
        <h2>What teleportation does</h2>

        <Callout label="Setup" tone="muted">
          <p>
            The protocol assumes Alice and Bob already share a Bell pair —
            one half in Alice's lab, the other in Bob's, however far apart
            those labs are. How that pair is delivered end-to-end is the
            question the <a href={url("/distribution")}>distribution</a> and
            <a href={url("/repeaters")}>repeaters</a> pages answer. For this
            page, take the shared Bell pair as given and watch what consuming
            it lets Alice do.
          </p>
        </Callout>

        <p>
          Alice has a qubit <strong>Q</strong> in some unknown state
          <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle = \\alpha|0\\rangle + \\beta|1\\rangle" />. She wants
          Bob to end up holding that same state. The setup: Alice and Bob already share a
          Bell pair — qubit <strong>A</strong> on Alice's side, qubit <strong>B</strong>
          on Bob's. Alice performs a <strong>Bell-state measurement (BSM)</strong> on her
          two qubits <strong>Q</strong> and <strong>A</strong>; this collapses them into
          one of the four Bell states and produces two classical bits
          <Math tex="(a, b)" />. The same instant the BSM fires, <strong>B</strong>
          becomes <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" /> — call it <Math tex="P(Q)" /> — where the
          Pauli <Math tex="P \\in \\{I, X, Z, ZX\\}" /> is fixed by the Bell-state outcome.
          Alice sends <Math tex="(a, b)" /> to Bob over a classical channel; Bob reads
          the bits, looks up which <Math tex="P^{-1}" /> they correspond to, and applies
          it to <Math tex="P(Q)" /> — which gives back <Math tex="Q" />, so
          <strong>B</strong> is now in <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. <strong>Q</strong> and <strong>A</strong> are
          consumed in the measurement and the Bell-pair entanglement is gone — exactly
          one copy of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> exists at any moment.
        </p>

        <figure class="tp" id="tp-fig" data-tp>
          <div class="tp-stage">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 630 270" role="img"
               aria-label="Quantum teleportation animation: Q and A photons drop into Alice's BSM box; bits travel to Bob who unlocks the Pauli-locked qubit B."
               data-tp-svg>
            <defs>
              <radialGradient id="tp-cloud-std" cx="0.5" cy="0.5" r="0.5">
                <stop offset="0%"   stop-color="var(--tp-teal)"   stop-opacity="0.95"/>
                <stop offset="40%"  stop-color="var(--tp-teal)"   stop-opacity="0.55"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--tp-teal)"   stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
              <radialGradient id="tp-cloud-psi" cx="0.5" cy="0.5" r="0.5">
                <stop offset="0%"   stop-color="var(--tp-purple)" stop-opacity="0.95"/>
                <stop offset="40%"  stop-color="var(--tp-purple)" stop-opacity="0.55"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--tp-purple)" stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
              <radialGradient id="tp-cloud-spent" cx="0.5" cy="0.5" r="0.5">
                <stop offset="0%"   stop-color="#7a8390" stop-opacity="0.9"/>
                <stop offset="40%"  stop-color="#7a8390" stop-opacity="0.45"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="#7a8390" stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
            </defs>

            {/* Endpoint labels */}
            <text x="170" y="22" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-label">Alice</text>
            <text x="560" y="22" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-label">Bob</text>

            {/* Subtle dashed region labels — just enough to delineate Alice's
                lab from Bob's, without a solid surface block dominating the
                figure. Sized to enclose only the actual content. */}
            <rect x="50"  y="34" width="240" height="220" rx="6"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"
                  stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.55"/>
            <rect x="500" y="34" width="120" height="100" rx="6"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"
                  stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.55"/>

            {/* Photon labels are inside each photon's <g> so they
                translate with the qubit during the animation — when
                Q and A fly into the BSM apparatus, their labels go
                with them. */}

            {/* Bob's qubit B sits in its endpoint, awaiting correction.
                Label rides with the group even though Bob doesn't move,
                for consistency. */}
            <g data-tp-b transform="translate(560 95)">
              <circle data-tp-b-cloud r="20" fill="url(#tp-cloud-std)"/>
              <text data-tp-b-label y="-26" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-slot-label">B</text>
            </g>

            {/* Entangled-pair wave A ↔ B */}
            <path data-tp-bellpair d="M 0 0" fill="none"
                  stroke="var(--tp-teal)" stroke-width="1.4" opacity="0.9"/>

            {/* BSM apparatus — scaled copy of images/BSM.svg geometry
                (viewBox 640×540).  Scale 197/640 ≈ 0.308 puts the two
                input ports at outer (130, 95) and (210, 95) — exactly
                the centres of Q and A above.  Diagonals are drawn as
                dotted strokes because they represent photon paths
                through the optics, not solid apparatus parts.  Inline
                stroke/fill attributes (with `currentColor` set on the
                nested SVG root) instead of a nested <style> tag —
                Astro's JSX context doesn't evaluate `<style>{`…`}</style>`
                inside SVG markup. */}
            <svg data-tp-bsm-rect x="71.54" y="79.62" width="197" height="166"
                 viewBox="0 0 640 540" overflow="visible" color="var(--color-text)">
              <defs>
                <symbol id="tp-bsm-detector" overflow="visible">
                  <path d="M -22,0 A 22,22 0 0 1 22,0 Z" fill="currentColor"/>
                </symbol>
              </defs>
              {/* Dotted photon-path diagonals through the apparatus. */}
              <line x1="190" y1="50"  x2="450" y2="310" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="310" x2="510" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="310" x2="390" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="50"  x2="190" y2="310" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="190" y1="310" x2="130" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="190" y1="310" x2="250" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              {/* Central 50:50 beam splitter (vertical bar at inner x=320). */}
              <rect x="312" y="140" width="16" height="80" rx="4" fill="currentColor"/>
              {/* Two polarising beam splitters — diamonds with vertical coating. */}
              <polygon points="190,270 230,310 190,350 150,310" fill="#d9eef9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              <line x1="190" y1="270" x2="190" y2="350" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <polygon points="450,270 490,310 450,350 410,310" fill="#d9eef9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="270" x2="450" y2="350" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              {/* Four detectors — D-shapes flat side perpendicular to incoming beam. */}
              <use href="#tp-bsm-detector" transform="translate(130,370) rotate(-135)"/>
              <use href="#tp-bsm-detector" transform="translate(250,370) rotate(135)"/>
              <use href="#tp-bsm-detector" transform="translate(390,370) rotate(-135)"/>
              <use href="#tp-bsm-detector" transform="translate(510,370) rotate(135)"/>
            </svg>

            {/* Q and A photons — rendered AFTER the apparatus so they
                travel above its beams and optical elements. */}
            <g data-tp-c transform="translate(130 95)">
              <circle data-tp-c-cloud r="20" fill="url(#tp-cloud-psi)"/>
              <text y="-26" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-slot-label">Q</text>
            </g>
            <g data-tp-a transform="translate(210 95)">
              <circle data-tp-a-cloud r="20" fill="url(#tp-cloud-std)"/>
              <text y="-26" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-slot-label">A</text>
            </g>

            {/* Classical channel — left end centred under the central BS
                bar (outer x≈170).  Label runs WELL below the dashed line
                so the (a, b) bit pulse (which rides at y≈215 above the
                line) doesn't visually cut the label as it slides past. */}
            <line x1="170" y1="222" x2="560" y2="222"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1"
                  stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.65"/>
            <text x="365" y="252" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-channel">classical channel · 2 bits</text>

            {/* Bit-pair (a, b) — rides along the classical channel */}
            <g data-tp-bits opacity="0">
              <text data-tp-bits-text x="170" y="215" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-bit">(0, 0)</text>
            </g>

            {/* Three stacked status lines centred in the gap between Alice
                and Bob (x≈370), well clear of the apparatus on the left
                and Bob on the right:
                 line 1 — "Q and A jointly measured → |Ψ⁺⟩"  (fires at BSM)
                 line 2 — "Q is teleported to Bob as P(Q)"   (same instant)
                 line 3 — "so Bob applies P⁻¹ to recover |ψ⟩" (fires when
                          the inverse chip flies up to cancel P).
                All three persist through the hold phase so the reader
                has time to follow the narrative end-to-end. */}
            <text data-tp-measure x="370" y="114" text-anchor="middle"
                  class="tp-statement" opacity="0"></text>
            <text data-tp-statement x="370" y="134" text-anchor="middle"
                  class="tp-statement" opacity="0"></text>
            <text data-tp-correction x="370" y="154" text-anchor="middle"
                  class="tp-statement" opacity="0"></text>

            {/* Bob's lock — ring around B with a Pauli letter tag. Appears
                the moment Alice's BSM fires. The ring is the visual cue
                that B is in P|ψ⟩, not |ψ⟩. */}
            <g data-tp-lock opacity="0">
              <circle cx="560" cy="95" r="24" fill="none"
                      stroke="var(--tp-purple)" stroke-width="2"
                      stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
              <g data-tp-lock-tag transform="translate(560 138)">
                <rect x="-20" y="-14" width="40" height="28" rx="4"
                      fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--tp-purple)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
                <text data-tp-lock-letter x="0" y="6" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-pauli-badge">P</text>
              </g>
            </g>

            {/* Inverse chip that materializes near the arriving bits
                and flies UP to cancel the Pauli badge on B. Same
                dimensions as the badge above so they overlay exactly. */}
            <g data-tp-inverse opacity="0">
              <rect x="-20" y="-14" width="40" height="28" rx="4"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--tp-purple)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <text data-tp-inverse-text x="0" y="6" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-pauli-badge">P⁻¹</text>
            </g>
          </svg>
            <aside class="tp-side-note">
              <strong>Which outcomes are shown</strong>
              <span>
                Only the <Math tex="|\\Psi^\\pm\\rangle" /> outcomes are animated — the
                two a linear-optics BSM can resolve, by firing two distinct detectors.
                The <Math tex="|\\Phi^\\pm\\rangle" /> outcomes bunch both photons onto
                one detector, are indistinguishable from each other, and in a real
                linear-optics BSM are the "failed" branches that consume the Bell pair
                without a usable teleport.
              </span>
            </aside>
          </div>

          <ol class="tp-step-list" data-tp-steps>
            <li data-tp-step="1"><strong>1.</strong> Alice has Q; A and B are a shared Bell pair</li>
            <li data-tp-step="2"><strong>2.</strong> Alice applies BSM on Q and A to get 2 classical bits (a, b); B becomes P|ψ⟩</li>
            <li data-tp-step="3"><strong>3.</strong> Bits travel to Bob</li>
            <li data-tp-step="4"><strong>4.</strong> Bob applies P⁻¹</li>
            <li data-tp-step="5"><strong>5.</strong> B holds |ψ⟩</li>
          </ol>

          <figcaption>
            <strong>Q</strong> (purple) is the qubit to teleport. <strong>A</strong> and
            <strong>B</strong> (teal) are halves of a shared Bell pair, drawn connected
            by the high-frequency wavy line. <strong>Q</strong> and <strong>A</strong>
            travel through Alice's BSM apparatus and arrive at two detectors; the path
            changes each cycle to match which pair of detectors fired. The two clouds
            turn grey because the original states are gone the moment the measurement
            begins. Two classical bits emerge on the channel below. At that same
            instant <strong>B</strong> turns purple, marked with the Pauli <em>P</em>
            the BSM outcome left on it — its state is now <Math tex="P(Q)" />.
            When the bits arrive at Bob, the matching <Math tex="P^{-1}" /> chip rises
            to meet that <em>P</em> badge and the two cancel. <strong>B</strong> now
            holds <strong>Q</strong>'s state.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <Callout label="Why the naive approaches fail">
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Measure and send.</strong> Reading <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> in any
              basis collapses it; the outcome reveals only one bit's worth of statistics, not
              the continuous complex amplitudes <Math tex="\\alpha" /> and
              <Math tex="\\beta" />. The qubit is left in a basis state and the information
              needed to recreate <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> is gone.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Copy and ship.</strong> No-cloning forbids creating a second qubit in
              the same unknown state.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Send the qubit physically.</strong> A photon carrying
              <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> can travel through fibre, but no-cloning rules
              out optical amplification — and at long distances loss compounds without an
              amplification mechanism that preserves quantum state.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="theory" data-nav-section>
        <h2>The theory</h2>
        <p>
          The starting resource is a Bell pair
          <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB} = (|00\\rangle + |11\\rangle)/\\sqrt{2}" />
          shared between Alice and Bob — Alice holds qubit <Math tex="A" />, Bob holds
          qubit <Math tex="B" />. Alice additionally holds the qubit
          <Math tex="Q" /> in the state <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> she wants to
          teleport. The protocol then proceeds in four steps:
        </p>

        <ol class="tp-steps">
          <li>
            <strong>Initial joint state.</strong> The three qubits together are
            <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle_Q \\otimes |\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB}" />. Re-expanding on
            <Math tex="Q, A" /> in the Bell basis,
            <Math display tex="|\\psi\\rangle_Q \\otimes |\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB} = \\tfrac{1}{2}\\bigl( |\\Phi^+\\rangle_{QA} |\\psi\\rangle_B + |\\Phi^-\\rangle_{QA} Z|\\psi\\rangle_B + |\\Psi^+\\rangle_{QA} X|\\psi\\rangle_B + |\\Psi^-\\rangle_{QA} ZX|\\psi\\rangle_B \\bigr)." />
            The state of the three qubits hasn't changed — this is the same vector written
            in a different basis. But it now exposes that <Math tex="B" /> is correlated
            with <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> up to a Pauli operator, indexed by which
            Bell state <Math tex="Q, A" /> sit in.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Bell-state measurement at Alice.</strong> Alice measures
            <Math tex="Q" /> and <Math tex="A" /> jointly in the Bell basis. The
            measurement projects them onto one of the four Bell states with equal
            probability ¼ and yields two classical bits
            <Math tex="(a, b)" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Classical communication.</strong> Alice sends <Math tex="(a, b)" /> to
            Bob over a classical channel. At this point Bob's qubit is in
            <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" /> — the right state up to a known Pauli operator
            <Math tex="P \\in \\{I, X, Z, ZX\\}" />.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Pauli correction at Bob.</strong> Bob applies <Math tex="X^b Z^a" />,
            which equals the inverse of <Math tex="P" />. His qubit is now in
            <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <p>
          The bit pattern <Math tex="(a, b)" /> tells Bob which Bell state Alice's BSM
          collapsed onto, and therefore which Pauli to apply:
        </p>

        <div class="tp-pauli-table-wrap">
        <table class="tp-pauli-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>(a, b)</th><th>BSM outcome</th><th>State at Bob (<Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" />)</th><th>Bob applies <Math tex="P^{-1}" /></th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>(0, 0)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="I^{-1} = I" /></td></tr>
            <tr><td>(0, 1)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Psi^+\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="X|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="X^{-1} = X" /></td></tr>
            <tr><td>(1, 0)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Phi^-\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="Z|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="Z^{-1} = Z" /></td></tr>
            <tr><td>(1, 1)</td><td><Math tex="|\\Psi^-\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="ZX|\\psi\\rangle" /></td><td><Math tex="(ZX)^{-1} = XZ" /></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        </div>
        <p class="tp-pauli-note">
          <Math tex="I" />, <Math tex="X" />, <Math tex="Z" /> are each their own inverse
          (<Math tex="X^2 = Z^2 = I" />); <Math tex="(ZX)^{-1} = X^{-1} Z^{-1} = XZ" />.
        </p>

        <Callout label="Does Bob already have |ψ⟩ after Alice's measurement?">
          <p>
            Not quite. The moment Alice's BSM fires, Bob's qubit is in
            <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" /> — one of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />,
            <Math tex="X|\\psi\\rangle" />, <Math tex="Z|\\psi\\rangle" />, or
            <Math tex="ZX|\\psi\\rangle" /> — and Bob doesn't yet know which. He cannot
            distinguish these four states from local measurements alone (his density
            matrix is <Math tex="\\tfrac{1}{2}\\mathbb{I}" /> regardless), so the qubit
            carries no usable information until the two bits arrive and he can apply
            <Math tex="P^{-1}" />. <em>Then</em> Bob holds <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />.
            Calling <Math tex="B" /> <q>the teleported qubit</q> before the correction is
            a shorthand — the state of the qubit at that moment is
            <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" />, not <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />.
          </p>
        </Callout>

      </section>

      <section id="circuit" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Circuit diagram</h2>
        <p>
          As a quantum circuit, the protocol runs on three wires — Alice's input qubit
          <Math tex="Q" />, Alice's half of the Bell pair <Math tex="A" />, and Bob's
          half <Math tex="B" /> — with time flowing left to right. The three conceptual
          stages are Bell-pair creation, the Bell-state measurement, and the Pauli
          correction <SourceNote id="cacciapuoti-ieeetc-2020" />.
        </p>

        <figure class="tp-circuit">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 760 280" role="img"
               aria-label="Teleportation circuit: Bell-pair creation, Bell-state measurement, and Pauli correction">

            {/* ─── Region labels (right side) ─────────────────── */}
            <text x="730" y="74" class="tp-c-region">Alice</text>
            <text x="730" y="134" class="tp-c-region">Alice</text>
            <text x="730" y="194" class="tp-c-region">Bob</text>

            {/* ─── Initial state labels (left) ─────────────────── */}
            <text x="40" y="76" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|ψ⟩</text>
            <text x="40" y="136" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|0⟩</text>
            <text x="40" y="196" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|0⟩</text>

            {/* ─── Quantum wires ───────────────────────────────── */}
            <line x1="50" y1="70"  x2="720" y2="70"  stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="50" y1="130" x2="720" y2="130" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="50" y1="190" x2="720" y2="190" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>

            {/* ─── Block 1: Bell-pair creation ─────────────────── */}
            <rect x="65" y="110" width="125" height="100" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <text x="127" y="100" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-block">Bell-pair |Φ⁺⟩ creation</text>

            {/* H on Alice's |0⟩ (middle wire) */}
            <rect x="85" y="120" width="22" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="96" y="135" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">H</text>

            {/* CNOT: control middle, target bottom */}
            <line x1="155" y1="130" x2="155" y2="190" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <circle cx="155" cy="130" r="4" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <circle cx="155" cy="190" r="9"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="146" y1="190" x2="164" y2="190" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="155" y1="181" x2="155" y2="199" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>

            {/* ─── Block 2: Bell-state measurement (BSM) ──────── */}
            <rect x="225" y="50" width="160" height="100" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <text x="305" y="42" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-block">Bell-state measurement</text>

            {/* CNOT: control top, target middle */}
            <line x1="245" y1="70" x2="245" y2="130" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <circle cx="245" cy="70" r="4" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <circle cx="245" cy="130" r="9"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="236" y1="130" x2="254" y2="130" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="245" y1="121" x2="245" y2="139" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>

            {/* H on top wire */}
            <rect x="280" y="60" width="22" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="291" y="75" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">H</text>

            {/* Measurement on top */}
            <rect x="335" y="60" width="32" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <path d="M 343 78 A 8 8 0 0 1 359 78" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <line x1="351" y1="78" x2="361" y2="64" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>

            {/* Measurement on middle */}
            <rect x="335" y="120" width="32" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <path d="M 343 138 A 8 8 0 0 1 359 138" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <line x1="351" y1="138" x2="361" y2="124" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1"/>

            {/* ─── Classical wires (double lines) ──────────────── */}
            {/* Top measurement → Z gate (label "a") */}
            <path d="M 367 68 H 638 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
            <path d="M 367 72 H 642 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>

            {/* Middle measurement → X gate (label "b") */}
            <path d="M 367 128 H 568 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>
            <path d="M 367 132 H 572 V 184" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="0.8"/>

            {/* Classical-bit labels on the wires */}
            <text x="500" y="62" class="tp-c-bit">a</text>
            <text x="465" y="122" class="tp-c-bit">b</text>

            {/* ─── Block 3: Pauli correction ──────────────────── */}
            <rect x="555" y="170" width="120" height="40" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <text x="615" y="227" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-block">Pauli correction</text>

            {/* X^b */}
            <rect x="565" y="180" width="28" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="579" y="195" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">X<tspan baseline-shift="super" font-size="9">b</tspan></text>

            {/* Z^a */}
            <rect x="635" y="180" width="28" height="20" rx="2"
                  fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <text x="649" y="195" text-anchor="middle" class="tp-c-gate">Z<tspan baseline-shift="super" font-size="9">a</tspan></text>

            {/* Final state label at right end of Bob's wire */}
            <text x="710" y="186" text-anchor="end" class="tp-c-state">|ψ⟩</text>

            {/* ─── Time arrow at bottom ───────────────────────── */}
            <line x1="50" y1="252" x2="720" y2="252" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="0.6"/>
            <polygon points="720,252 714,249 714,255" fill="var(--color-rule)"/>
            <text x="50" y="266" class="tp-c-time">time →</text>
          </svg>
          <figcaption>
            <strong>Bell-pair creation:</strong> a Hadamard on Alice's
            <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /> followed by a CNOT onto Bob's
            <Math tex="|0\\rangle" /> produces the Bell pair
            <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB}" />.
            <strong>Bell-state measurement:</strong> a CNOT, a Hadamard, and two
            single-qubit measurements project Alice's <Math tex="Q" /> and
            <Math tex="A" /> jointly onto a Bell state, yielding two classical bits —
            <em>a</em> from the <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> measurement, <em>b</em>
            from the Bell-half measurement. Double lines are the classical wires
            carrying those bits to Bob.
            <strong>Pauli correction:</strong> Bob applies <Math tex="X^b" /> followed
            by <Math tex="Z^a" /> to undo the Pauli operator the BSM outcome left on his
            qubit, completing the transfer of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> onto
            <Math tex="B" />.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section id="math" data-nav-section>
        <h2>No faster-than-light shortcut</h2>
        <p>
          The instant non-locality of entanglement was exactly what Einstein,
          Podolsky and Rosen objected to in their 1935 paper — Einstein later
          dismissed it as <q>spukhafte Fernwirkung</q>, <em>spooky action at a
          distance</em>. Teleportation looks like a natural test case for that
          worry: Alice's BSM instantaneously fixes Bob's qubit into
          <Math tex="P|\\psi\\rangle" />. So why doesn't it let Alice signal
          superluminally by choosing what to measure?
        </p>
        <p>
          Before Alice's classical message arrives, Bob's qubit <Math tex="B" />
          is in a uniform mixture of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />,
          <Math tex="X|\\psi\\rangle" />, <Math tex="Z|\\psi\\rangle" />, and
          <Math tex="ZX|\\psi\\rangle" /> — its local density matrix is
          <Math tex="\\tfrac{1}{2}\\mathbb{I}" />, the maximally mixed state,
          regardless of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" />. Bob's local statistics are
          independent of Alice's outcome, so he learns nothing about
          <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> from his half alone. Only when he
          receives the two bits and applies the matching correction does the
          qubit become useful. Teleportation is therefore compatible with
          relativity — no information crosses faster than the classical bits
          do, and Einstein's worry survives as a piece of intuition about a
          phenomenon that turns out to obey the speed limit after all.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="ledger" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Resources and limits</h2>
        <p>
          Each teleported qubit consumes a fixed budget:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>1 Bell pair</strong>, consumed in Alice's BSM. The Bell pair is the
            quantum resource — getting it to both ends is the network's job
            (covered in the distribution and links subjects).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>2 classical bits</strong>, sent over a classical channel from Alice to
            Bob. The classical message is what makes teleportation no faster than light.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>The original <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> at Alice, gone.</strong>
            Alice's BSM projects <Math tex="Q" /> and <Math tex="A" /> jointly onto a Bell
            state, leaving no copy of <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> at Alice — consistent
            with no-cloning. In photonic BSM the <Math tex="Q" /> and <Math tex="A" />
            photons are absorbed at the detectors; in matter implementations (trapped ions,
            NV centres) the qubits remain physically but are now in a known Bell state with
            each other. Either way, exactly one copy of the state exists in the protocol at
            any time <SourceNote id="wootters-nature-1982" />.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>Two consequences follow from this resource ledger:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Teleportation inherits the Bell pair's fidelity.</strong> A noisy
            pair gives Bob a noisy copy of <strong>Q</strong>'s state; the cleaner the
            pair, the cleaner the teleported state. This is why purification exists —
            to take noisy pairs and produce cleaner ones.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>One Bell pair per qubit, no reuse.</strong> The protocol is one-shot:
            each teleport consumes its Bell pair entirely. Teleporting many qubits
            requires many Bell pairs, which is why entanglement-distribution rate
            (Bell pairs per second) is the standard network rate metric.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="role" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Network role</h2>
        <p>
          Teleportation sits at the boundary between the network and the application.
          The network promises one thing: deliver Bell pairs at adequate rate, fidelity,
          and reach. The application's "send a qubit" operation is implemented by
          teleportation on top of that promise. Other applications — entanglement-based
          QKD, blind quantum computing, distributed quantum computing — also consume
          delivered Bell pairs; teleportation is the simplest case of using
          one <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two related primitives, covered in their own subjects, share teleportation's
          BSM machinery:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Entanglement swapping</strong> uses a BSM at a Bell-state analyser (BSA) to
            extend a Bell pair across an extra hop, without any of the four end-to-end
            qubits ever interacting. Memory-based repeaters chain swaps to span long
            distances. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>swapping</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Purification</strong> applies local CNOTs and measurements at both
            ends of a noisy pair to trade two low-fidelity pairs for one higher-fidelity
            pair. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>purification</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

<script type="module" is:inline>
  // Teleportation animation. Visual storyline:
  //   1. Setup — Alice has Q (purple cloud = |ψ⟩) and A (standard
  //      cloud, Bell half). Bob has B (standard cloud, Bell half).
  //      Entangled-wave connects A and B.
  //   2. BSM — Q and A travel along the apparatus beams (C through
  //      the BS to the far-right detector; A symmetrically to the
  //      far-left detector). Their clouds turn grey on entry — the
  //      original states are gone once they touch the apparatus.
  //      Bits (a, b) emerge from the apparatus. At the same instant,
  //      B picks up a purple tint with a "P" badge — physically it's
  //      now in P|ψ⟩, even though Bob doesn't know which P.
  //   3. Classical send — (a, b) travels along the classical line.
  //   4. Correction — bits arrive at Bob; the P badge drops, B turns
  //      fully purple = |ψ⟩ on Bob.
  //   5. Hold final state, reset.
  const fig = document.querySelector("[data-tp]");
  if (fig) {
    const svg          = fig.querySelector("[data-tp-svg]");
    const photonC      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-c]");
    const photonA      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-a]");
    const cCloud       = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-c-cloud]");
    const aCloud       = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-a-cloud]");
    const bCloud       = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-b-cloud]");
    const bLabel       = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-b-label]");
    const bellLine     = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bellpair]");
    const measureLine  = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-measure]");
    const statement    = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-statement]");
    const correction   = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-correction]");
    const lock         = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-lock]");
    const lockLetter   = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-lock-letter]");
    const inverse      = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-inverse]");
    const inverseText  = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-inverse-text]");
    const bitsGroup    = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bits]");
    const bitsText     = svg.querySelector("[data-tp-bits-text]");
    const stepEls      = Array.from(fig.querySelectorAll("[data-tp-step]"));

    // Photon paths through the BSM apparatus. Starts coincide with
    // the apparatus input ports (= cloud centres at y=95). The path
    // is two legs: input → BS centre → one of four detectors. Which
    // detector depends on the cycle's outcome (Ψ⁺ or Ψ⁻ only — see
    // OUTCOMES and the figcaption note).
    const C_HOME = { x: 130, y: 95 };
    const A_HOME = { x: 210, y: 95 };
    const B_HOME = { x: 560, y: 95 };
    const BS_POS = { x: 170, y: 135 };       // central beam-splitter centre, outer coords
    const DET = {
      H1: { x: 111.5, y: 193.6 },           // far-left detector
      V1: { x: 148.6, y: 193.6 },           // left-inner detector
      V2: { x: 191.7, y: 193.6 },           // right-inner detector
      H2: { x: 228.7, y: 193.6 },           // far-right detector
    };
    // Set per cycle by pickCycleParams() based on the outcome.
    const C_END = { x: DET.H2.x, y: DET.H2.y };
    const A_END = { x: DET.H1.x, y: DET.H1.y };
    const LOCK_POS    = { x: 560, y: 138 };  // P-badge centre, not cloud centre
    const BIT_X_START = 170;
    const BIT_X_END   = LOCK_POS.x;          // aligned so the chip flies STRAIGHT UP

    // High-frequency sinewave along the line from A's right edge to B's
    // left edge. Rebuilt each frame while A is moving so the wave
    // stretches and tilts with A.
    function rebuildBellLine(ax, ay, bx, by) {
      const dx = bx - ax, dy = by - ay;
      const len = Math.hypot(dx, dy);
      if (len < 1) { bellLine.setAttribute("d", ""); return; }
      const nx = -dy / len, ny = dx / len;  // unit perpendicular
      const wavelength = 14, amp = 5;
      // Dense sampling (~2 px per segment) so the sine is rendered, not
      // collapsed onto its zero-crossings.
      const segments = Math.max(40, Math.round(len / 2));
      let d = `M ${ax} ${ay}`;
      for (let i = 1; i < segments; i++) {
        const t = i / segments;
        const baseX = ax + dx * t;
        const baseY = ay + dy * t;
        const phase = (t * len / wavelength) * 2 * Math.PI;
        const off = Math.sin(phase) * amp;
        d += ` L ${baseX + nx * off} ${baseY + ny * off}`;
      }
      d += ` L ${bx} ${by}`;
      bellLine.setAttribute("d", d);
    }
    rebuildBellLine(A_HOME.x + 20, A_HOME.y, B_HOME.x - 22, B_HOME.y);

    function setPos(g, x, y) { g.setAttribute("transform", `translate(${x} ${y})`); }

    // Bell outcome (a,b) → state ket, Pauli operator. Matches the
    // (a,b) → P table in the prose. Bob applies P⁻¹ which equals P
    // for I, X, Z (self-inverse) and equals XZ for ZX (up to sign).
    // `P` is the residual operator on Bob's qubit (state = P|ψ⟩);
    // `inv` is what Bob actually applies, i.e. P⁻¹. For I/X/Z the
    // Paulis are self-inverse so inv === P; for ZX, inv = XZ.
    // We animate only the Ψ⁺ and Ψ⁻ outcomes — the two cases where the
    // BSM produces two clicks at distinct detectors (the success cases
    // of a linear-optics photonic BSM).  Φ⁺ and Φ⁻ bunch both photons
    // at a single detector and are not resolvable here; see the
    // figcaption.  Each Ψ outcome has two click variants — the photons
    // are indistinguishable after the BS, so each variant is equally
    // physical.  The cycle iterates through all four variants in order.
    const OUTCOMES = [
      { a: 0, b: 1, ket: "|Ψ⁺⟩", P: "X",  inv: "X",  clicks: ["H1", "V1"] },
      { a: 0, b: 1, ket: "|Ψ⁺⟩", P: "X",  inv: "X",  clicks: ["H2", "V2"] },
      { a: 1, b: 1, ket: "|Ψ⁻⟩", P: "ZX", inv: "XZ", clicks: ["H1", "V2"] },
      { a: 1, b: 1, ket: "|Ψ⁻⟩", P: "ZX", inv: "XZ", clicks: ["V1", "H2"] },
    ];
    let outcomeIndex = -1;

    const reducedMotion = matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;

    function setOpacity(el, op) { el.setAttribute("opacity", String(op)); }
    function highlightStep(n) {
      for (const el of stepEls) {
        el.classList.toggle("tp-step--active", Number(el.dataset.tpStep) === n);
      }
    }
    function setBitsX(x) { bitsText.setAttribute("x", String(x)); }

    if (reducedMotion) {
      const o = OUTCOMES[1];
      bitsText.textContent  = `(${o.a}, ${o.b})`;
      setOpacity(photonC, 0);
      setOpacity(photonA, 0);
      setOpacity(bellLine, 0.15);
      setOpacity(bitsGroup, 0);
      setOpacity(lock, 0);
      bCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-psi)");
      if (bLabel) bLabel.textContent = "Q";
      highlightStep(5);
    } else {
      const T_SETUP   = 1000;
      const T_DROP    = 1100;  // Q and A traverse the BSM apparatus
      const T_MEASURE = 1100;  // bits emerge, lock appears on B
      const T_SEND    = 1700;  // bits slide along classical channel
      const T_UNLOCK  = 1100;  // inverse tag flies up to lock, both vanish
      const T_HOLD    = 2400;  // long enough to read the 3-line narrative
      const T_PAUSE   = 400;
      const T_TOTAL   = T_SETUP + T_DROP + T_MEASURE + T_SEND + T_UNLOCK + T_HOLD + T_PAUSE;

      let cycleStart = 0;
      let outcome = OUTCOMES[0];
      function ease(t) {
        return t < 0.5 ? 4 * t * t * t : 1 - Math.pow(-2 * t + 2, 3) / 2;
      }
      // Two-leg interpolation: first 40 % runs start → mid, remaining
      // 60 % runs mid → end.  Photons take an explicit kink at the BS
      // for outcomes that send them to the opposite side of the apparatus.
      function twoLeg(start, mid, end, t) {
        if (t < 0.4) {
          const k = t / 0.4;
          return { x: start.x + (mid.x - start.x) * k, y: start.y + (mid.y - start.y) * k };
        }
        const k = (t - 0.4) / 0.6;
        return { x: mid.x + (end.x - mid.x) * k, y: mid.y + (end.y - mid.y) * k };
      }

      function pickCycleParams() {
        // Cycle through all four Ψ-outcome variants deterministically.
        outcomeIndex = (outcomeIndex + 1) % OUTCOMES.length;
        outcome = OUTCOMES[outcomeIndex];
        bitsText.textContent  = `(${outcome.a}, ${outcome.b})`;
        lockLetter.textContent = outcome.P;
        inverseText.textContent = outcome.inv;
        measureLine.textContent = `Q and A jointly measured`;
        statement.textContent = `Q is teleported to Bob as ${outcome.P}(Q)`;
        correction.textContent = `so Bob applies ${outcome.inv} to recover Q`;
        bCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-std)");
        cCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-psi)");
        aCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-std)");
        // Q goes to the first detector in the click pair, A to the second.
        // (Photons are indistinguishable after the BS; this fixes a
        // labelling so each cycle looks deterministic.)
        const cClick = outcome.clicks[0];
        const aClick = outcome.clicks[1];
        C_END.x = DET[cClick].x;  C_END.y = DET[cClick].y;
        A_END.x = DET[aClick].x;  A_END.y = DET[aClick].y;
        setPos(photonC, C_HOME.x, C_HOME.y);
        setPos(photonA, A_HOME.x, A_HOME.y);
      }

      function frame(now) {
        const elapsed = now - cycleStart;
        let t0 = T_SETUP;

        if (elapsed < t0) {
          // Phase 1 — setup. Everything in starting positions.
          highlightStep(1);
          setOpacity(photonC, 1);
          setOpacity(photonA, 1);
          setPos(photonC, C_HOME.x, C_HOME.y);
          setPos(photonA, A_HOME.x, A_HOME.y);
          cCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-psi)");
          aCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-std)");
          rebuildBellLine(A_HOME.x + 20, A_HOME.y, B_HOME.x - 22, B_HOME.y);
          setOpacity(bellLine, 0.9);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, 0);
          setOpacity(lock, 0);
          setOpacity(inverse, 0);
          setOpacity(measureLine, 0);
          setOpacity(statement, 0);
          setOpacity(correction, 0);
          bCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-std)");
          if (bLabel) bLabel.textContent = "B";
        } else if (elapsed < (t0 += T_DROP)) {
          // Phase 2a — Q and A traverse the BSM apparatus in two legs:
          // input port → BS centre, then BS → their assigned detector.
          // Which detectors fire is set by the cycle's outcome, so the
          // photon paths change from cycle to cycle.  Clouds turn grey
          // on entry: the original states are gone the moment they
          // touch the apparatus.
          highlightStep(2);
          const t = (elapsed - (t0 - T_DROP)) / T_DROP;
          const e = ease(t);
          // Two legs: first 40 % of the eased timeline takes the photon
          // from its input port to the BS centre, remaining 60 % from
          // BS to the assigned detector.
          const cPos = twoLeg(C_HOME, BS_POS, C_END, e);
          const aPos = twoLeg(A_HOME, BS_POS, A_END, e);
          setPos(photonC, cPos.x, cPos.y);
          setPos(photonA, aPos.x, aPos.y);
          // First ~20 % of the traversal: fade the clouds from their
          // original colours to grey.
          if (e < 0.2) {
            const k = e / 0.2;
            if (k > 0.5) {
              cCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-spent)");
              aCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-spent)");
            }
          } else {
            cCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-spent)");
            aCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-spent)");
          }
          // Bell pair line stays anchored at the A↔B start positions
          // (don't rebuild) and simply fades — moving photons no longer
          // drag the wave across the figure and overlay the captions.
          setOpacity(bellLine, Math.max(0, 0.9 * (1 - e * 1.4)));
          // "Q and A jointly measured → |Ψ±⟩" fades in as the photons
          // start moving — the BSM is happening now, not after they
          // land at the detectors.
          setOpacity(measureLine, Math.min(1, e * 2));
        } else if (elapsed < (t0 += T_MEASURE)) {
          // Phase 2b — measurement. Photons fade out at the detectors,
          // bits emerge under the apparatus, B picks up the Pauli badge,
          // the statement "Q is teleported to Bob as P(Q)" fades in.
          highlightStep(2);
          const t = (elapsed - (t0 - T_MEASURE)) / T_MEASURE;
          const e = ease(t);
          setOpacity(photonC, Math.max(0, 1 - e * 2));
          setOpacity(photonA, Math.max(0, 1 - e * 2));
          setOpacity(bellLine, 0);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, Math.max(0, (e - 0.3) * 2));
          setBitsX(BIT_X_START);
          // B turns purple, Pauli badge appears, and the label flips
          // from "B" to the explicit Pauli-twisted state P(Q) as soon
          // as the BSM fires — B is no longer in its original state.
          bCloud.setAttribute("fill", "url(#tp-cloud-psi)");
          if (bLabel) bLabel.textContent = `${outcome.P}(Q)`;
          setOpacity(lock, Math.min(1, e * 2.5));
          setOpacity(measureLine, 1);            // already faded in during phase 2a
          setOpacity(statement, Math.min(1, e * 2));
        } else if (elapsed < (t0 += T_SEND)) {
          // Phase 3 — bits slide right along classical channel.
          highlightStep(3);
          const t = (elapsed - (t0 - T_SEND)) / T_SEND;
          setOpacity(photonC, 0);
          setOpacity(photonA, 0);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, 1);
          setBitsX(BIT_X_START + (BIT_X_END - BIT_X_START) * t);
          setOpacity(lock, 1);
          setOpacity(inverse, 0);
          setOpacity(measureLine, 1);
          setOpacity(statement, 1);
        } else if (elapsed < (t0 += T_UNLOCK)) {
          // Phase 4 — bits arrive; an inverse tag materialises at the
          // bit position and flies UP to the lock; both vanish on contact.
          highlightStep(4);
          const t = (elapsed - (t0 - T_UNLOCK)) / T_UNLOCK;
          const e = ease(t);
          setBitsX(BIT_X_END);
          // Inverse appears at the bit position, flies up to the lock.
          const ix = BIT_X_END;
          const iy_start = 222;  // bits row (now lifted up under the BSM)
          const iy_end   = LOCK_POS.y;  // lock centre
          const ix_end   = LOCK_POS.x;
          const ix_now   = ix + (ix_end - ix) * e;
          const iy_now   = iy_start + (iy_end - iy_start) * e;
          setPos(inverse, ix_now, iy_now);
          // The "so Bob applies P⁻¹" line fades in as the inverse chip
          // takes off — same time the reader needs the prompt.
          setOpacity(correction, Math.min(1, e * 2));
          // Inverse visible during the flight; chip and lock fade
          // together once the chip reaches the badge (e ≈ 0.85).  The
          // three narrative lines stay up — they describe what just
          // happened, and need the hold phase to be readable.
          const fadeT = Math.max(0, (e - 0.85) / 0.15);
          setOpacity(inverse, 1 - fadeT);
          setOpacity(lock,    1 - fadeT);
          // Inverse chip and lock vanish together — at the midpoint of
          // that fade B has effectively absorbed P⁻¹ and now holds Q.
          if (bLabel && fadeT > 0.5) bLabel.textContent = "Q";
          setOpacity(measureLine, 1);
          setOpacity(statement, 1);
          // Bits dissolve as they're "consumed".
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, Math.max(0, 1 - e * 1.5));
        } else if (elapsed < T_TOTAL - T_PAUSE) {
          // Phase 5 — hold.  B is purple, lock and bits gone; the three
          // narrative lines stay visible for the entire hold so the
          // reader has time to read them before the cycle resets.
          highlightStep(5);
          setOpacity(bitsGroup, 0);
          setOpacity(lock, 0);
          setOpacity(inverse, 0);
          setOpacity(measureLine, 1);
          setOpacity(statement, 1);
          setOpacity(correction, 1);
          if (bLabel) bLabel.textContent = "Q";
        } else if (elapsed < T_TOTAL) {
          // Brief fade-out tail so the lines don't blink off on reset.
          const t = (elapsed - (T_TOTAL - T_PAUSE)) / T_PAUSE;
          const a = Math.max(0, 1 - t);
          setOpacity(measureLine, a);
          setOpacity(statement, a);
          setOpacity(correction, a);
        } else if (elapsed >= T_TOTAL) {
          cycleStart = now;
          pickCycleParams();
        }
        requestAnimationFrame(frame);
      }

      pickCycleParams();
      cycleStart = performance.now();
      requestAnimationFrame(frame);
    }
  }
</script>

